diff:1612391671:1612379318:=63,77d62%0a%3c #foxbegin 210203-223431-991160#%0a%3c (:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c [-03.02.2021 - 14:34-] &nbsp; %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c !!!!!Connor_G%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c '''Why base-10?'''%0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c%0a%3c That raises an equally interesting question—why is base-10 the norm? The leading theory is that, as silly as it sounds, the fact that we have 10 fingers made it most effective for early humans to count things in tens! This intuition stayed with us as we came to develop number systems!%0a%3c %0a%3c That being said, there are even early examples of of civilizations using other bases (consider the base-60 system from Babylon that our minutes and hours system is inherited from). Is it possible that the key to using non base-10 systems is having a writing system to represent it? %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210203-223431-991160#%0a
